{{Infobox person | name = Horst Geicke | image = 2016-11-01, Deutsches Haus HCM, Topping out event, press conference Horst Geicke, smaller.jpg | image_size = 300 | caption = Horst Geicke (2016) with the press at topping out Deutsches Haus Ho Chi Minh Stadt | birth_date = 1955 | birth_place = Hamburg, [[Germany]] | residence = Ho Chi Minh City, Vietnam | nationality = German | occupation = Businessman, Functionary, Chairman of the German House Ho Chi Minh City }}
'''Horst Joachim Franz Geicke''' (born 1955 in [[Hamburg]]) is a [[Germans|German-born]] [[entrepreneur]], [[investor]], and [[official]] in [[Asia]].<ref name="Chamber">[http://www.eurocham.com.hk/about-ecc/the-european-chamber-of-commerce-in-hong-kong-2016-vice-chairman "Profile Horst Geicke"], ''The European Chamber of Commerce in Hong Kong''</ref> He is currently building the [[Deutsches Haus Ho Chi Minh Stadt]] as chairman and Investor.
Geicke studied Business Administration and Business Law at the [[University of Hamburg]] and moved to [[Hong Kong]] in 1981 to be a successful entrepreneur with export-oriented manufacturing companies in China.<ref name="Handelsblatt">[https://global.handelsblatt.com/edition/56/ressort/companies-markets/article/aiming-high-in-ho-chi-minh-city "Aiming High in Ho Chi Minh City"], [[Handelsblatt]]</ref> Later, he focused on investments, particularly in real estate along [[Richard Li]]. He also founded VinaCapital Investment Management, Euro Auto (BMW Vietnam), and the Pacific Alliance Group (PAG).<ref name="FAZ">[http://horstgeicke.com/de/faz-wie-ein-deutscher-milliarden-in-asien-investiert/ "Wie ein Deutscher Milliarden in Asien investiert"], [[Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung]] (German)</ref><ref name="Bloomberg">[https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=20523238&privcapId=250031777 "Executive Profile"], [[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]]</ref> He is known as an early investor in China as well as in Vietnam and with this expertise mentioned in newspapers.<ref>[https://www.forbes.com/2010/03/30/vietnam-investment-property-emerging-markets-real-estate-jonathan-choi.html "Buy Vietnam"], [[Forbes]]</ref><ref>[https://www.forbes.com/2008/10/29/china-richest-billionaires-biz-chinarichest08-cx_rf_1029chinaintro.html "China's 400 Richest"], [[Forbes]]</ref><ref>[http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-8671046.html "China erwacht, die Welt erbebt"], [[Der Spiegel]] (German)</ref> In 2015 he was ranked 270 of the richest Germans by [[Manager Magazin]].<ref>[http://horstgeicke.com/de/manager-magazin-die-500-reichsten-deutschen/ "Die 500 reichsten Deutschen"], [[Manager Magazin]] (German)</ref>
Today, Geicke is primarily known as chairman and investor of the Deutsches Haus Ho Chi Minh City. The building complex which is scheduled to be completed by 2017 consists of two towers with an estimated investment of €100 million.<ref name="Handelsblatt" /><ref>[http://www.vir.com.vn/deutsches-haus-a-lighthouse-for-german-vietnamese-partnership.html "Deutsches Haus - A lighthouse for German-Vietnamese partnership"], ''Vietnam Investment Review''</ref> It was initiated under a bilateral government agreement between Germany and Vietnam.<ref>[https://www.bundesregierung.de/Content/EN/Artikel/2014/10_en/2014-10-15-bkin-empfaengt-pm-vietnam_en.html;jsessionid=6DD63616723A720E97E7D7E547DFAA6F.s1t1 "Bringing the partnership to life"], ''Federal Government of Germany''</ref><ref>[http://www.thanhniennews.com/business/germany-builds-a-home-in-ho-chi-minh-city-eyes-investment-opportunities-52932.html "Germany builds a home in Ho Chi Minh City, eyes investment opportunities"], ''thanhniennews.com''</ref> This centrally located property had been purchased in 1960 by the German government. Geicke then acquired the property from the German federal government, which was originally intended for “diplomatic purposes” in Ho Chi Minh city against initial resistance of the Vietnamese party bureaucracy and by negotiating with the German federal ministries. Geicke had previously acquired federal property in Hong Kong.<ref name="FAZ" />
Geicke is an active member of business communities. In Hong Kong, he is and was president of the European and [[Association of German Chambers of Industry and Commerce|German Chamber of Commerce]]. He is also president of the Hong Kong Vietnam Chamber of Commerce and board member of other organizations.<ref name="Chamber" /><ref>[http://hongkong.ahk.de/chamber/committee-members "Committee Members"], ''German Chamber of Commerce, Hong Kong''</ref><ref>[http://www.hk-thai.com/hkthai/jsp/en/council/governors.jsp "Directors"], ''Hong Kong-Thailand Business Council''</ref><ref>[http://info.hktdc.com/hk-europe/member_hk.htm "Members"], ''Hong Kong-Europe Business Council''</ref>
In Vietnam, he founded the VinaCapital Foundation which is engaged in the social sector, such as the financing of cardiac surgery as a late consequence of the Vietnam War (“Heartbeat Vietnam”).<ref name="Bloomberg" /><ref>[https://www.vietnambreakingnews.com/tag/horst-geicke/ "Articles Vietnam Breaing News"], ''vietnambreakingnews.com''</ref>
