[[Image:Izrael Kalmanowicz Poznański.jpg|thumb]] '''Izrael Kalman Poznański''' (1833 in [[Aleksandrow Lodzki|Aleksandrów]] &ndash; 1900 in [[Łódź]]) was a [[Polish Jews|Polish-Jewish]] businessman, [[textile]] [[magnate]] and [[philanthropist]] in Łódź, and the husband of Elenora Hertz Poznański.<ref>Muzeum Historii Żydów Polskich (Museum of the History of Polish Jews). [http://www.sztetl.org.pl/en/person/27,izrael-kalmanowicz-poznanski/ "Poznanski Izrael Kalmanowicz"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150121040628/http://www.sztetl.org.pl/en/person/27,izrael-kalmanowicz-poznanski/ |date=2015-01-21 }}. Retrieved 15 November 2013.</ref> The mausoleum of Izrael and Eleonora Hertz Poznański on the [[Jewish Cemetery, Łódź|New Jewish Cemetery]] has been described as "probably the largest Jewish grave monument in the world."<ref>Wojalski, Mirosław Zbigniew (2000). [https://books.google.com/books?id=gn4tAQAAIAAJ&q=%22Izrael+Pozna%C5%84ski%22+mausoleum&dq=%22Izrael+Pozna%C5%84ski%22+mausoleum&hl=en&sa=X&ei=NwaGUu_MCYPF7AamxoDYBQ&ved=0CDcQ6AEwAQ ''The Jewish cemetery in Lodz''], p.58. Widzewska Oficyna Wydawnicza ZORA. {{ISBN|8388638017}}. Quote: "Across from this sarcophagus stands the magnificent mausoleum of Izrael Poznanski. The largest and most impressive grave monument in this cemetery, and probably the largest Jewish grave monument in the world".</ref> The mausoleum and [[mosaic]] covering the inside of the dome were restored in 1993.
His complex of mills in [[ Łódź]], Poland, have been turned into the {{convert|69|ha|adj=on}} [[Manufaktura]] [[mixed-use development]], including a mall, 3 museums, multi-cinema and restaurants.
